A case of hypoglossal and glossopharyngeal palsy

#case
#neuro

History:
Mrs. P
35 year old lady with two children, housewife.

Previously healthy.

Developed sudden onset slurring of speech.
Presented to a private sector doctor 5 days later and was found to have tongue deviation.
AAR for MRI date.

No DM, DL or HT.
No history suggestive of connective tissue disease.
No history of miscarriages.
No smoker
No history of substance abuse
No migrain history
Father died of ACS at 51 years old.
Mother died due to complication of LRT surgery - but patient is uncertain about the exact cause

No dysautonomic symptoms suggestive of glossopharyngeal nerve damage but that would need bilateral glossopharyngeal damage, wouldn't it?

Examination:

  • Tongue deviation to left side and subtle uvular deviation to the right side.
  • Other cranial nerves and peripheral nerves are in tact.
  • Gag reflex not checked.
  • no cerebellar signs on either side
  • Dual rhythm, no murmurs and no carotid bruits

Normotensive - no history of hypertension
CBS normal.

Investigations:
NCCT - no ICH.

Management:

  • Initially managing as ischemic stroke.
  • Patient was started on clopidogrel 75 and atorvastatin 40.

What else to look for:

  • vasculitis
  • embolic source
  • arrhythmia

Lecture on geriatric medicine by GMA

what is a "comprehensive geriatric assessment"?

There is an "Elderly secretariat" in colombo which oversees the 300 odd local "elderly committees".

CGA is done for frail, older adults. (Not robust older adults)
These patient will have one or more of

  1. Falls
  2. Immobility
  3. Delerium and dementia
  4. Polypharmacy (> 5 drugs)
  5. Incontinence
  6. End if life care

I.e: The "Geriatric giants" - 5i's

Patient who will not benefit from cga:

  1. Dementia
  2. Terminally ill
  3. Robus elderly

CGA is used to determine medical, psychological and functional status.

CGA is not needed for a patient who is only old but has good functional status.

Components of cognitive assessment

  • MMSE is a key part
  • Mini cog test
  • Clock drawing test

Dementia, delerium and depression (big Ds in elderly care).

ADLs assessment: barthel index
And IADLs
And AADLs

Nutritional assessment

  1. Mini nutritional assessment
  2. MUST score

Polypharmacy may be appropriate or inappropriate.

  • Check "falls risk increasing drugs"

Thrombocytopaenia in pregnancy

#lecture

[!NOTE] Summary

Definition: PLT < 150k.
Plt < 100 is rare.
< 80 is very rare.

Plt < 70 is very rare in gestational thrombocytopenia.

Hypertensive disposers have moderate low plt. Counts are usually above 50.

If plt < 50,
Think about ITP, TTP and bone marrow failure.

Mechanism:
Haemodikution, increased destruction and sequestration cause low plt.

Pregnancy associated causes or general thrombocytopenic causes

In each category, low plt is either isolated or associated with systemic manifestations.
DDs are different for each category.

Two important questions:

  1. trimester of onset.
  2. Severity of the thrombocytopenia

Management of cirrhosis

prognosis in cirrhosis

The median survival of patients with compensated cirrhosis is >12 years.

Varices + but no bleeding -> classified as "compensated".
But having even un ruptured varices is a poor prognostic factor.

Patients who have developed variceal hemorrhage, ascites, spontaneous bacterial peritonitis, hepatocellular carcinoma, hepatorenal syndrome, or hepatopulmonary syndrome, are considered to have decompensated cirrhosis and have a worse prognosis than those with compensated cirrhosis.

Complications of cirrhosis

  • Variceal hemorrhage
    •Ascites
    •Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis
    • Prevention -
      • Adequate diuresis - concentration of ascitic opsonins
      • Minimize PPI use
      • Detect and treat any infections early

•Hepatic encephalopathy
•Hepatocellular carcinoma
•Hepatorenal syndrome
•Hepatopulmonary syndrome
•Portal vein thrombosis
•Cardiomyopathy

  • Hyponatremia -
    • stop antihypertensives including beta blockers
    • Correct hypokalemia - why?
    • BP can be increased if hypotensive with midodrine (alpha agonist)
  • hypocoagulable state or a hypercoagulable state
    • INR and APTT are not useful in assessing the bleeding risk in clcd patients.
    • Plt > 50,000 if a procedure it to be done

[!INFO] Analgesia in liver failure
Only pcm is safe but half-life may be prolonged
Opioids can be used but may precipitate hepatic encephalopathy.
NSAIDs should ve avoided due to risk of GI bleeds and renal failure.

Maintenance fluids

Medscape Calculator -> based on the 4-2-1 rule.

[!INFO] This translates to: For a 70 Kg adult;

  • water - 2100 ml / day (2100 / 24 = 85 ml/hr)
  • Na, potassium, chloride - all 70 mmol / day (yes, 70 mmol of K+ per day seems a lot but it's verified)
    • LITFL says Na requirement is 2 mmol/Kg/day
  • Glucose - 3500 to 7000 g / day.
    • (5% glucose = 5g / 100 ml)
    • Understanding drug dilutions: Source
  • Hospitalized patients who are afebrile, not eating, and physically inactive require less than one liter of electrolyte (sodium and potassium)-free water as maintenance fluid. -UpToDate
    • That would be only 40 cc / hr.
    • water requirements increase by 100 to 150 mL/day for each degree of body temperature elevation over 37°C.

Fluid resuscitation

500 ml over < 15 minutes.

Insensible water loss

Estimated at 50ml/hr for an adult. Source

Glossopharyngeal nerve

CN IX has motor AND sensory components.
Source-Video

Hypoglossal nerve


Exits the cranium through the hypoglossal canal in the occipital bone and then travels above the hyoid and then under the tongue.
It is a motor nerve, innervating all the intrinsic muscles and all but one of the extrinsic muscles of the tongue.
Palsy causes ipsilateral tongue deviation. (Like your wounds).

  • resolution will take a few months with treatment.

  • of the various immunosuppressants, only MMF and MTX are contraindicated in pregnancy.

Lente insulin for comparison:

Insulin regimes

The goal is to mimic physiological insulin release as much as possible.

  • BIDS regime - oral hypoglycaemic + single basal insulin dose.

    • Use either bed time isophane or morning long acting analogs.
    • Isophane action lasts 16 hours.
    • Analogs - 24 hours.
    • Starting dose - 10 units or 0.2 units / Kg.
    • increase by 2 units every 3 days.
    • If glucose < 80, reduced bed time dose by 4 units or 10%, whichever is greater.

  • Basal bolus regime -> basal insulin and 3 boluses (most effective)

    • Most effective regime - used in GDM
    • Adds a short acting insulin dose to cover post prandial hyperglycaemia
    • Use soluble insulin or a rapid actin insulin.
      • Peak comes in 2 hours, lasts 6 hours.
      • Requires tds blood glucose to customize insulin doses for each meal.
    • 4 injections per day so patient compliance will be poor.

  • premixed insulin twice a day -> not very effective.

    • Short acting and regular insulin before breakfast and before dinner
    • However, Sri Lankan patients have a carb heavy lunch.
    • Control of the The post lunch hyperglycaemia relies on the morning dose.

Management of acute hyperglycaemia:

  • Insulin infusion protocols
  • CRP - is an [[2023-SEMPaper#Acute phase reactants|Acute phase reactant]].
  • Roles:
    • Has proinflammatory and anti-inflammatory properties. Anti > pro!
    • Identifies and binds to foreign molecules and damaged local cells. ⭐Activates the classical [[#Complement system|complement]] pathway AND binds Fc receptors to facilitate phagocytosis - opsonin
    • It "enhances cell mediated immunity by promoting phagocytosis, accelerating chemotaxis, and activating platelets".
  • Increases within 2 hours of an insult. Half life of 18 hours.

Clinical practice

[!clinic] My Experience

  • Step 1: Clinical evaluation of suspected pneumonia
    • Arrive at a possible diagnosis of LRTI
  • Step 2: Assess severity with CURB 65 to determine the setting for management
  • Step 4: Is it typical or atypical or viral?
    • Table above for typical and atypical pathogens and presentation.
    • Typical or atypical may be based on history and examination. Viral or not will be determined by FBC.
    • If typical, try to determine the most likely pathogen:
      • "bacterial causes of CAP, such as MRSA, Enterobacteriaceae, and Pseudomonas aeruginosa, tend to be associated with greater illness severity and are detected more frequently in hospitalized patients and those with specific risk factors."
    • i.e patients with risk factors and/or severe features should get a sputum culture.
      • the risk factors for klebsiella pneumonia are "diabetes mellitus, alcoholism, malignancy, hepatobiliary disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, renal failure, and glucocorticoid therapy".
      • Risk factors for pseudomonas: ⬆age, smoking, alcohol, bronchiectasis, recent hospitalization, intubation, cirrhosis
      • In the case of bronchiectasis, pseudomonas found in the sputum culture may just be a colonizer!
  • Step 4: Clinical practice is to start antibiotics which provide typical and atypical cover
  • Step 5: Monitor for recovery - When to repeat the CXR?

Clinical entities to distinguish:

  • pneumonia due to typical bacteria
  • Pneumonia due to atypical bacteria
  • Viral pneumonia
  • Staph pneumonia

How the microbiology lab performs sputum cultures:

  • They first analyze the sputum sample for the presence of pus cells. More pus cells = better sample. Few pus cells -> Poor sample.
  • Good samples are cultured.
  • The colonies are then gram stained an identified.
  • They used two types of agar: enriched media and non enriched media.


Overall effects : increased contractile velocity (increased contractility) and decreased heart rate.

  1. Heart failure - inhibition of Na/K ATPase -> increased intra-myocyte sodium -> decreased Na calcium exchange -> reduced secretion of calcium -> increased intracellular calcium -> contractility increased.
  • However, elevated intracellular calcium also increases risk of arrhythmias.
    Antiarrhythmic - slows conduction through the AV node, increases vagal tone. This property is used to slow the ventricular rate in patients with persistent AF.
  • The preceding two changes are caused by decreases in the atrial and ventricular refractory periods and alterations in ventricular repolorization.
    Drug has a large Vd. so it's makes sense that it exerts it's effects on [cardiac] muscle.
  • Renal dysfunction increases digoxin levels and often precipitate toxicity!
  • Hyperkalemia (inhibition of Na/K ATPase),
  • Hypokalemia
  • Side effect: Gynaecomastia
  • Frequent PVCs - premature ventricular contractions (the most common abnormality), including ventricular bigeminy and trigeminy
